Linking Providers

Source: vignettes/linking_providers.Rmd
linking_providers.Rmd
library(provider)
library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(knitr)

Exploring links between providers can lead to many interesting insights. For example, there is a hospital in New York named Elizabethtown Community Hospital.

Looking it up in the Provider Enrollment API gives us several avenues to go down:

provider_enrollment(organization_name = "Elizabethtown Community Hospital") |> kable()
npi pac_id enroll_id specialty_code specialty state organization_name
1891785184 3577554138 O20040521000534 12-70 PART B SUPPLIER - CLINIC/GROUP PRACTICE NY ELIZABETHTOWN COMMUNITY HOSPITAL
1891785184 3577554138 O20101110000259 00-85 PART A PROVIDER - CRITICAL ACCESS HOSPITAL NY ELIZABETHTOWN COMMUNITY HOSPITAL
1487923637 3577554138 O20190719002511 12-59 PART B SUPPLIER - AMBULANCE SERVICE SUPPLIER NY ELIZABETHTOWN COMMUNITY HOSPITAL
1407061591 3577554138 O20220827000145 00-85 PART A PROVIDER - CRITICAL ACCESS HOSPITAL NY ELIZABETHTOWN COMMUNITY HOSPITAL

First, we can see that it has one PAC ID, three different organizational NPIs, and four different Enrollment IDs. Looking it up in the Hospital Enrollment API gives us even more detail:

hospital_enrollment(organization_name = "Elizabethtown Community Hospital") |> 
  select(-c(address:subgroups, specialty, organization_structure, proprietary_nonprofit)) |> 
  kable()
npi pac_id_org enroll_id facility_ccn specialty_code organization_name enroll_state multiple_npis
1891785184 3577554138 O20101110000259 331302 00-85 ELIZABETHTOWN COMMUNITY HOSPITAL NY TRUE
1407061591 3577554138 O20220827000145 33Z302 00-85 ELIZABETHTOWN COMMUNITY HOSPITAL NY FALSE

The Hospital Enrollment API includes only Medicare Part A (hospital) providers, so we only get two rows back, but those include a new data point: two facility CCNs. Plugging those into the Facility Affiliations API, we can retrieve information on the individual providers practicing at this hospital. First, the all-numeric CCN (331302):

facility_affiliations(facility_ccn = 331302) |> 
  select(-c(middle_name, suffix)) |> 
  kable()

That returns 174 individual providers affiliated with the Hospital. Now the alphanumeric CCN (33Z302):

facility_affiliations(facility_ccn = "33Z302") |> 
  select(-c(middle_name)) |> 
  kable()
npi pac_id_ind first_name last_name facility_type facility_ccn parent_ccn
1396989059 8921259557 MARY HALLORAN Nursing home 33Z302 331302
1538173869 0547299091 IL CHON Nursing home 33Z302 331302
1801893318 3577568724 ROB DEMURO Nursing home 33Z302 331302

That returns three more affiliated individual providers that practice in the Hospitalâ€™s nursing home. An alphanumeric CCN represents a sub-unit of a Hospital, here a Nursing Home. We would get the same result if weâ€™d set the parent_ccn argument to the numeric CCN:

facility_affiliations(parent_ccn = 331302)
